{
  "text": "Most of previous studies included only patients with primary APS. Nevertheless, Agmon et al. [CITATION_1] also included patients with secondary APS. They showed that those with secondary APS had lower vitD levels than patients with primary APS, and both of them lower than controls. This fact could be explained by the sun avoidance and the use of sunscreens in patients with SLE the presence of renal disease, or the use of some medications such as steroids. Overall, the finding of low vitD levels in APS patients keeps in line with the suggested role of vitD in the pathogenesis of many autoimmune conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis, diabetes or multiple sclerosis [CITATION_2] . In fact, it is well known that vitamin D has regulatory properties in the immune system. Thus, it regulates the differentiation and activation of CD4+ lymphocytes, inhibits the differentiation of dendritic cells, as well as the differentiation from monocytes to macrophages, preventing them from releasing inflammatory cytokines and chemokines [CITATION_3] . Besides, vitD deficiency is associated with impaired TLR function in aged subjects [CITATION_4] . Moreover, it reduces IL-12 production and so, IL12-mediated Th1 responses and the production of IFN-gamma and IL-2 [CITATION_5] . On the other hand, it increases IL-10 and promotes Th2 type T helper function. Regarding B cells, vitD has",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "25704693",
    "[CITATION_2]": "3194048",
